daily at 3 p.m., with COVID-19 results included as of 10 a.m..<br>\n{{Note label|Note2|b|b}} Patients are not residents, but are being treated within the state of Michigan.</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.michigan.gov/coronavirus Coronavirus information] from the State of Michigan\n* [https://www.mlive.com/news/jackson/2020/03/updated-maps-michigan-coronavirus-cases-and-exposure-sites.html Updated maps: Michigan coronavirus cases and exposure sites] from MLive.com\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Michigan]]\n[[Category:2020 in Michigan|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Health in Michigan]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Denisebk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApril 1\u20137", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Michigan"}
{"title_page": "Dublin\u2013Navan railway line", "text_new": "{{Use Irish English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n|name        = Dublin to Navan line\n|color       =\n|logo        =\n|logo_width  =\n|image       = Spencer Dock North End - geograph.org.uk - 847797.jpg\n|image_width = \n|caption     = A section of the line in the Dublin Docklands\n|type        = [[Commuter rail]], [[Suburban rail]]\n|system      = [[Iarnr\u00f3d \u00c9ireann]]\n|status      = Operational\n|locale      = Ireland\n|start       = [[Docklands railway station|Docklands]] \n|end         = [[M3 Parkway railway station|M3 Parkway]]\n|stations    = 10\n|routes      = \n|daily_ridership =\n|open        = 3 September 2010\n|close       =\n|owner       = [[Iarnr\u00f3d \u00c9ireann]] \n|operator    = [[Iarnr\u00f3d \u00c9ireann]]<br>[[Commuter (Iarnr\u00f3d \u00c9ireann)|Commuter]]\n|character   = Secondary\n|depot       = \n|stock       = [[IE 29000 Class|29000 Class]]<br>[[IE 22000 Class|22000 Class]] \n|linelength_km = 64\n|tracklength =\n|tracks      = [[Double track]]\n|gauge       = {{track gauge|1600mm}} [[Irish gauge]] \n|electrification = Not electrified \n|speed       = \n|elevation   =\n|map         = {{Dublin-Navan railway line|inline=1}}\n|map_state   = collapsed\n|box_width   = \n}}\nThe '''Dublin-Navan line''' (via Clonsilla) is a partially-open [[commuter rail]] line between [[Dublin]] and the town of [[Navan]] in [[County Meath]]. Since September 2010, train services operate from Docklands Station to M3 Parkway, with an extension to Navan itself proposed.\n\n== History ==\n===Background===\nNavan was originally a significant part of the expanding [[Rail transport in Ireland|rail network]] in [[Ireland]]. The [[Dublin and Drogheda Railway]] first constructed a branch from the [[Dublin-Belfast railway line|Dublin-Belfast main line]] through Navan to the town of [[Oldcastle, County Meath|Oldcastle]] which opened in 1850. In 1862, the Dublin and Meath Railway constructed and operated a branch from [[Clonsilla]] to Navan off the [[Midland Great Western Railway|MGWR]] main line to [[Sligo]]. This line was extended to [[Kingscourt railway station|Kingscourt]] in [[County Cavan]] in 1865, operated by the [[Navan and Kingscourt Railway]]. Both of these lines were eventually purchased by the MGWR, while the Oldcastle line was eventually incorporated into the [[Great Northern Railway (Ireland)|GNR(I)]]. [[Navan railway station]] itself was a small single platform stop on the Oldcastle line.<ref>[http://eiretrains.com/Photo_Gallery/Railway%20Stations%20N/Navan/IrishRailwayStations.html Navan station] - eiretrains.com</ref> The main station for the town was [[Navan Junction railway station|Navan Junction]], which had four platforms serving trains on both routes.<ref>[http://eiretrains.com/Photo_Gallery/Railway%20Stations%20N/Navan%20Junction/IrishRailwayStations.html Navan Junction station] - eiretrains.com</ref> \n\nIn the 1950s and 1960s, there was a large scale rationalisation of the railway network in Ireland, which saw [[C\u00f3ras Iompair \u00c9ireann]] close large sections of line. Passenger services on the Kingscourt line were ended in 1947, while on the Oldcastle line they continued until 1958. The lines from Clonsilla and Oldcastle to Navan was lifted in 1963, with the remainder remaining open for freight use following the withdrawal of passenger services - the Gypsum Industries plant in Kingscourt utilised the line as far as Navan Junction before transferring to the Oldcastle line to transport [[gypsum]] to the Platin Cement Works just outside [[Drogheda]], while the [[Tara Mine]] also uses the Oldcastle branch to transport [[lead]] and [[zinc]]. Following industrial action by Iarnr\u00f3d \u00c9ireann train drivers in 2001, Gypsum freight services from Kingscourt were transferred to [[road haulage]], which led to the remainder of the line being mothballed. The line has been preserved however, with the then Minister for Public Enterprise, Mary O'Rourke TD, ordering Iarnr\u00f3d \u00c9ireann not to 'lift' the railway line, as it may be used in the future.\n\n===Initial proposal and opening to M3 Parkway===\nThe growth of the economy in [[County Meath]], added to the increase in the population of Navan,<ref>[http://www.cso.ie/census/documents/census2006_volume_1_pop_classified_by_area.pdf Census 2006 \u2013 Volume 1 \u2013 Population Classified by Area] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717202529/http://www.cso.ie/census/documents/census2006_volume_1_pop_classified_by_area.pdf |date=17 July 2011 }}</ref> has led to calls over the past few years for a rail service to be reinstated from Dublin. \n\nAs part of the [[Transport 21]] plan announced by the [[Irish Government]] in 2005, the line to Navan would be rebuilt in two phases as a branch of the [[Dublin Suburban Rail|Western Commuter]] line. The first phase would see a 7.5&nbsp;km stretch from the junction west of [[Clonsilla railway station|Clonsilla]]. This would feature three new railway stations at [[Hansfield railway station|Hansfield]], [[Dunboyne]] and [[park and ride]] interchange called [[M3 Parkway railway station|M3 Parkway]]. This became operational in September 2010.<ref>[http://www.transport21.ie/PROJECTS/HEAVY_RAIL/Navan_Rail_Line.html Transport 21 - Navan Rail Line] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080204063113/http://www.transport21.ie/PROJECTS/HEAVY_RAIL/Navan_Rail_Line.html |date=4 February 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Extension to Navan===\n{{Navan railways}}\nThe second phase was originally planned to be completed by 2030, but as of 2019 is deferred subject to \"review\".<ref name=\"chronicle\">{{cite web|url= https://www.meathchronicle.ie/news/roundup/articles/2019/08/26/4178700-planning-minister-asks-that-navan-rail-line-priority-be-downgraded/|title= Planning minister asks that Navan Rail line priority be downgraded|website=Meath Chronicle|date=26 August 2019|accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref> If completed as planned it would see the line extended from M3 Parkway to [[Navan]] itself, with further stations at [[Dunshaughlin]], [[Kilmessan]] and two in Navan (provisionally titled Navan Central and Navan North).<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.irishrail.ie/index.jsp?p=186&n=188 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120509065511/http://www.irishrail.ie/index.jsp?p=186&n=188 | archivedate = 9 May 2012 | publisher = Irish Rail | website = irishrail.ie | title = Projects & Investment - Navan Railway Line - Drawings & Schematics }}</ref> The former, Navan Central, was proposed to be located near [[P\u00e1irc Tailteann]].<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.irishrail.ie/projects/pdf/navan/Navan%20Central%20option.pdf | title = Navan Central option | publisher = Irish Rail | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110606130115/http://www.irishrail.ie/projects/pdf/navan/Navan%20Central%20option.pdf | archivedate = 6 June 2011}}</ref> Plans expected that the latter station, Navan North, would be the northern terminus of a reinstated line.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.irishrail.ie/projects/pdf/navan/Navan%20North%20option.pdf | title = Map - Navan North Option | website = irishrail.ie | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110606130250/http://www.irishrail.ie/projects/pdf/navan/Navan%20North%20option.pdf | archivedate = 6 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.irishrail.ie/projects/pdf/navan/Route%20alignment%20options.pdf | title = Map - Route Alignment Options| website = irishrail.ie | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110606125934/http://www.irishrail.ie/projects/pdf/navan/Route%20alignment%20options.pdf| archivedate = 6 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\nSince the early 21st century, [[Docklands railway station|Docklands]] has served as the terminus for peak time services on the Western Commuter originating from M3 Parkway.<ref>[http://www.transport21.ie/PROJECTS/HEAVY_RAIL/Docklands_Rail_Station.html Transport 21 - Docklands Railway Station] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080110092152/http://www.transport21.ie/PROJECTS/HEAVY_RAIL/Docklands_Rail_Station.html |date=10 January 2008 }}</ref> The proposal would have seen this station expanded to become the main terminus for Western Commuter services, including from Navan, as well as a stop for planned DART services through the [[DART Underground]]. However, in 2007, [[Iarnr\u00f3d \u00c9ireann]] announced plans to restore rail services to the long closed [[Dublin Broadstone railway station|Dublin Broadstone]] station - it was this that I\u00c9 planned to use as its major terminus for commuter services from {{stnlnk|Mullingar}} and Navan.<ref>[http://blogs.mobhaile.ie/leobollins/archive/2007/06/10/242044.aspx Broadstone to Live Again] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080120212956/http://blogs.mobhaile.ie/leobollins/archive/2007/06/10/242044.aspx |date=20 January 2008 }}</ref> \n\nIn March 2008, the transport minister blocked these proposals in favour of utilising Broadstone for the [[Luas]] system, instead encouraging I\u00c9 to seek planning permission to keep {{stnlnk|Docklands}} in place as the terminus for the Navan line, as well as services from {{stnlnk|Maynooth}} and {{stnlnk|Kildare}}.<ref>[http://buckplanning.blogspot.com/2008/02/dempsey-derails-ambitious-ci-plan-and.html Dempsey derails ambitious CI\u00c9 plan and opts for new Luas line] - Irish Times, 06/02/08</ref> As part of the wider improvements to the commuter network around Dublin, the line is proposed to be electrified as far as M3 Parkway and will form part of the planned [[Dublin Area Rapid Transit|DART]] Line 1.\n\nBy 2019, no progress had been made regarding the proposed Navan extension. The Irish government's regional spatial strategy recommended that year that the status of the plans be downgraded from \"implementation\" to \"review\"; seen as a setback to the opening of the line.<ref name=\"chronicle\"/>\n\n== Criticism ==\n{{Drogheda-Navan railway line}}\nAlthough the proposal to reinstate a rail service between Dublin and Navan has been welcomed, particularly in view of the comparison of cost with the M3 motorway (estimated to be \u20ac650 million against \u20ac90 million for the railway),<ref>[http://www.tarataratara.net/TARA_pdfs/MeathByRail.pdf Meath by rail...why not?]</ref> there has been criticism of the details of the proposal by the pressure group [[Platform 11|Rail Users Ireland]] (formerly ''Platform 11'').<ref>[http://www.railusers.ie/campaigns/navan/navan_drogheda.php Navan Already Has a Rail Line to Dublin]</ref> This group's alternative proposal would see the relaying of the line to standards necessary for passenger trains, the installation of two new stations, together with the reopening of [[Navan railway station|Navan station]].{{fact|date=December 2019}}\n\nCriticism has also been levelled at [[Meath County Council]], with Rail Users Ireland pointing out that part of the rail alignment planned to Navan was obstructed by the installation of a [[sanitary sewer|sewer main]].<ref>[http://www.railusers.ie/campaigns/navan/response.php Meath CC admit blocking alignment]</ref><ref>[http://www.railusers.ie/campaigns/navan/problems.php Clonsilla-Navan: It's No Certainty]</ref> The group has also suggested that, given the two-phase approach to implementing the plan, there is little benefit to residents of Navan until the line is extended there, due to the current positioning of the [[toll house|toll]] collection points near M3 Parkway station. In addition to this station being {{convert|30|km|mi}} from Navan itself, the toll point is positioned before drivers reach the station.<ref>[http://www.railusers.ie/campaigns/navan/ A Rail Service for Navan]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120508210658/http://www.irishrail.ie/index.jsp?p=124&n=186 Irish Rail Navan Rail information page]\n{{Railway lines in Eire}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dublin-Navan railway line}}\n[[Category:Rail transport in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Railway lines in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Proposed railway lines in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 2010]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Irish English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n|name        = Dublin to Navan line\n|color       =\n|logo        =\n|logo_width  =\n|image       = Spencer Dock North End - geograph.org.uk - 847797.jpg\n|image_width = \n|caption     = A section of the line in the Dublin Docklands\n|type        = [[Commuter rail]], [[Suburban rail]]\n|system      = [[Iarnr\u00f3d \u00c9ireann]]\n|status      = Operational\n|locale      = Ireland\n|start       = [[Docklands railway station|Docklands]] \n|end         = [[M3 Parkway railway station|M3 Parkway]]\n|stations    = 10\n|routes      = \n|daily_ridership =\n|open        = 3 September 2010\n|close       =\n|owner       = [[Iarnr\u00f3d \u00c9ireann]] \n|operator    = [[Iarnr\u00f3d \u00c9ireann]]<br>[[Commuter (Iarnr\u00f3d \u00c9ireann)|Commuter]]\n|character   = Secondary\n|depot       = \n|stock       = [[IE 29000 Class|29000 Class]]<br>[[IE 22000 Class|22000 Class]] \n|linelength_km = 64\n|tracklength =\n|tracks      = [[Double track]]\n|gauge       = {{track gauge|1600mm}} [[Irish gauge]] \n|electrification = Not electrified \n|speed       = \n|elevation   =\n|map         = {{Dublin-Navan railway line|inline=1}}\n|map_state   = collapsed\n|box_width   = \n}}\nThe '''Dublin-Navan line''' (via Clonsilla) is a partially-open [[commuter rail]] line between [[Dublin]] and the town of [[Navan]] in [[County Meath]]. Since September 2010, train services operate from Docklands Station to M3 Parkway, with an extension to Navan itself proposed.\n\n== History ==\n===Background===\nNavan was originally a significant part of the expanding [[Rail transport in Ireland|rail network]] in [[Ireland]]. The [[Dublin and Drogheda Railway]] first constructed a branch from the [[Dublin-Belfast railway line|Dublin-Belfast main line]] through Navan to the town of [[Oldcastle, County Meath|Oldcastle]] which opened in 1850. In 1862, the Dublin and Meath Railway constructed and operated a branch from [[Clonsilla]] to Navan off the [[Midland Great Western Railway|MGWR]] main line to [[Sligo]]. This line was extended to [[Kingscourt railway station|Kingscourt]] in [[County Cavan]] in 1865, operated by the [[Navan and Kingscourt Railway]]. Both of these lines were eventually purchased by the MGWR, while the Oldcastle line was eventually incorporated into the [[Great Northern Railway (Ireland)|GNR(I)]]. [[Navan railway station]] itself was a small single platform stop on the Oldcastle line.<ref>[http://eiretrains.com/Photo_Gallery/Railway%20Stations%20N/Navan/IrishRailwayStations.html Navan station] - eiretrains.com</ref> The main station for the town was [[Navan Junction railway station|Navan Junction]], which had four platforms serving trains on both routes.<ref>[http://eiretrains.com/Photo_Gallery/Railway%20Stations%20N/Navan%20Junction/IrishRailwayStations.html Navan Junction station] - eiretrains.com</ref> \n\nIn the 1950s and 1960s, there was a large scale rationalisation of the railway network in Ireland, which saw [[C\u00f3ras Iompair \u00c9ireann]] close large sections of line. Passenger services on the Kingscourt line were ended in 1947, while on the Oldcastle line they continued until 1958. The lines from Clonsilla and Oldcastle to Navan was lifted in 1963, with the remainder remaining open for freight use following the withdrawal of passenger services - the Gypsum Industries plant in Kingscourt utilised the line as far as Navan Junction before transferring to the Oldcastle line to transport [[gypsum]] to the Plantin Cement works just outside [[Drogheda]], while the [[Tara Mine]] also uses the Oldcastle branch to transport [[lead]] and [[zinc]]. Following industrial action by Iarnr\u00f3d \u00c9ireann train drivers in 2001, Gypsum freight services from Kingscourt were transferred to [[road haulage]], which led to the remainder of the line being mothballed. The line has been preserved however, with the then Minister for Public Enterprise, Mary O'Rourke TD, ordering Iarnr\u00f3d \u00c9ireann not to 'lift' the railway line, as it may be used in the future.\n\n===Initial proposal and opening to M3 Parkway===\nThe growth of the economy in [[County Meath]], added to the increase in the population of Navan,<ref>[http://www.cso.ie/census/documents/census2006_volume_1_pop_classified_by_area.pdf Census 2006 \u2013 Volume 1 \u2013 Population Classified by Area] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717202529/http://www.cso.ie/census/documents/census2006_volume_1_pop_classified_by_area.pdf |date=17 July 2011 }}</ref> has led to calls over the past few years for a rail service to be reinstated from Dublin. \n\nAs part of the [[Transport 21]] plan announced by the [[Irish Government]] in 2005, the line to Navan would be rebuilt in two phases as a branch of the [[Dublin Suburban Rail|Western Commuter]] line. The first phase would see a 7.5&nbsp;km stretch from the junction west of [[Clonsilla railway station|Clonsilla]]. This would feature three new railway stations at [[Hansfield railway station|Hansfield]], [[Dunboyne]] and [[park and ride]] interchange called [[M3 Parkway railway station|M3 Parkway]]. This became operational in September 2010.<ref>[http://www.transport21.ie/PROJECTS/HEAVY_RAIL/Navan_Rail_Line.html Transport 21 - Navan Rail Line] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080204063113/http://www.transport21.ie/PROJECTS/HEAVY_RAIL/Navan_Rail_Line.html |date=4 February 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Extension to Navan===\n{{Navan railways}}\nThe second phase was originally planned to be completed by 2030, but as of 2019 is deferred subject to \"review\".<ref name=\"chronicle\">{{cite web|url= https://www.meathchronicle.ie/news/roundup/articles/2019/08/26/4178700-planning-minister-asks-that-navan-rail-line-priority-be-downgraded/|title= Planning minister asks that Navan Rail line priority be downgraded|website=Meath Chronicle|date=26 August 2019|accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref> If completed as planned it would see the line extended from M3 Parkway to [[Navan]] itself, with further stations at [[Dunshaughlin]], [[Kilmessan]] and two in Navan (provisionally titled Navan Central and Navan North).<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.irishrail.ie/index.jsp?p=186&n=188 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120509065511/http://www.irishrail.ie/index.jsp?p=186&n=188 | archivedate = 9 May 2012 | publisher = Irish Rail | website = irishrail.ie | title = Projects & Investment - Navan Railway Line - Drawings & Schematics }}</ref> The former, Navan Central, was proposed to be located near [[P\u00e1irc Tailteann]].<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.irishrail.ie/projects/pdf/navan/Navan%20Central%20option.pdf | title = Navan Central option | publisher = Irish Rail | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110606130115/http://www.irishrail.ie/projects/pdf/navan/Navan%20Central%20option.pdf | archivedate = 6 June 2011}}</ref> Plans expected that the latter station, Navan North, would be the northern terminus of a reinstated line.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.irishrail.ie/projects/pdf/navan/Navan%20North%20option.pdf | title = Map - Navan North Option | website = irishrail.ie | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110606130250/http://www.irishrail.ie/projects/pdf/navan/Navan%20North%20option.pdf | archivedate = 6 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.irishrail.ie/projects/pdf/navan/Route%20alignment%20options.pdf | title = Map - Route Alignment Options| website = irishrail.ie | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110606125934/http://www.irishrail.ie/projects/pdf/navan/Route%20alignment%20options.pdf| archivedate = 6 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\nSince the early 21st century, [[Docklands railway station|Docklands]] has served as the terminus for peak time services on the Western Commuter originating from M3 Parkway.<ref>[http://www.transport21.ie/PROJECTS/HEAVY_RAIL/Docklands_Rail_Station.html Transport 21 - Docklands Railway Station] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080110092152/http://www.transport21.ie/PROJECTS/HEAVY_RAIL/Docklands_Rail_Station.html |date=10 January 2008 }}</ref> The proposal would have seen this station expanded to become the main terminus for Western Commuter services, including from Navan, as well as a stop for planned DART services through the [[DART Underground]]. However, in 2007, [[Iarnr\u00f3d \u00c9ireann]] announced plans to restore rail services to the long closed [[Dublin Broadstone railway station|Dublin Broadstone]] station - it was this that I\u00c9 planned to use as its major terminus for commuter services from {{stnlnk|Mullingar}} and Navan.<ref>[http://blogs.mobhaile.ie/leobollins/archive/2007/06/10/242044.aspx Broadstone to Live Again] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080120212956/http://blogs.mobhaile.ie/leobollins/archive/2007/06/10/242044.aspx |date=20 January 2008 }}</ref> \n\nIn March 2008, the transport minister blocked these proposals in favour of utilising Broadstone for the [[Luas]] system, instead encouraging I\u00c9 to seek planning permission to keep {{stnlnk|Docklands}} in place as the terminus for the Navan line, as well as services from {{stnlnk|Maynooth}} and {{stnlnk|Kildare}}.<ref>[http://buckplanning.blogspot.com/2008/02/dempsey-derails-ambitious-ci-plan-and.html Dempsey derails ambitious CI\u00c9 plan and opts for new Luas line] - Irish Times, 06/02/08</ref> As part of the wider improvements to the commuter network around Dublin, the line is proposed to be electrified as far as M3 Parkway and will form part of the planned [[Dublin Area Rapid Transit|DART]] Line 1.\n\nBy 2019, no progress had been made regarding the proposed Navan extension. The Irish government's regional spatial strategy recommended that year that the status of the plans be downgraded from \"implementation\" to \"review\"; seen as a setback to the opening of the line.<ref name=\"chronicle\"/>\n\n== Criticism ==\n{{Drogheda-Navan railway line}}\nAlthough the proposal to reinstate a rail service between Dublin and Navan has been welcomed, particularly in view of the comparison of cost with the M3 motorway (estimated to be \u20ac650 million against \u20ac90 million for the railway),<ref>[http://www.tarataratara.net/TARA_pdfs/MeathByRail.pdf Meath by rail...why not?]</ref> there has been criticism of the details of the proposal by the pressure group [[Platform 11|Rail Users Ireland]] (formerly ''Platform 11'').<ref>[http://www.railusers.ie/campaigns/navan/navan_drogheda.php Navan Already Has a Rail Line to Dublin]</ref> This group's alternative proposal would see the relaying of the line to standards necessary for passenger trains, the installation of two new stations, together with the reopening of [[Navan railway station|Navan station]].{{fact|date=December 2019}}\n\nCriticism has also been levelled at [[Meath County Council]], with Rail Users Ireland pointing out that part of the rail alignment planned to Navan was obstructed by the installation of a [[sanitary sewer|sewer main]].<ref>[http://www.railusers.ie/campaigns/navan/response.php Meath CC admit blocking alignment]</ref><ref>[http://www.railusers.ie/campaigns/navan/problems.php Clonsilla-Navan: It's No Certainty]</ref> The group has also suggested that, given the two-phase approach to implementing the plan, there is little benefit to residents of Navan until the line is extended there, due to the current positioning of the [[toll house|toll]] collection points near M3 Parkway station. In addition to this station being {{convert|30|km|mi}} from Navan itself, the toll point is positioned before drivers reach the station.<ref>[http://www.railusers.ie/campaigns/navan/ A Rail Service for Navan]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120508210658/http://www.irishrail.ie/index.jsp?p=124&n=186 Irish Rail Navan Rail information page]\n{{Railway lines in Eire}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dublin-Navan railway line}}\n[[Category:Rail transport in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Railway lines in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Proposed railway lines in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 2010]]\n", "name_user": "Philaper", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInitial proposal and opening to M3 Parkway:Corrected spelling and title of Platin Cement Works", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dublin%E2%80%93Navan_railway_line"}
{"title_page": "Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on prisons", "text_new": "{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] has impacted prisons''' around the world.\n\n==Afghanistan==\nThe Afghan government released 10,000 prisoners, mostly women, young people, the critically ill, and inmates over 55 on March 26, 2020.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/afghanistan-release-10-000-prisoners-slow-coronavirus-spread-211850224.html Afghanistan to release up to 10,000 prisoners to slow coronavirus spread] AFP, 26 March 2020</ref>\n\n==Australia==\nOn 16 March, the ACT government declared a public health emergency.{{cn|date=March 2020}} It has also planned to cancel all visits to the [[Alexander Maconochie Centre|Alexander Maconochie]] prison from March 23. ACT Corrective Services Commissioner Jon Peach stated that as a result there would be \"increased access to telephones\" for prisoners to keep in touch with their families.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-21/canberra-records-new-cases-of-covid-19-prison-visits-stopped/12077734|title=Canberra coronavirus cases increase as Health Minister halts prison visits|publisher=ABC News|date=21 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Brazil==\n\nHundreds of prisoners (who work outside the prison during the day) escaped from four prisons in [[S\u00e3o Paulo state]] after visitors were restricted and Easter furloughs were cancelled due to health concerns.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/17/come-back-monday-ok-hundreds-of-prisoners-escape-in-brazil-amid-covid-19-anger 'Come back Monday, OK?' Hundreds of prisoners escape in Brazil amid Covid-19 anger]</ref>\n\n==China==\n\nThe virus spread in at least four prisons in China.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Vivian |last2=McNeil Jr |first2=Donald G. |last3=Fassihi |first3=Farnaz |last4=Myers |first4=Steven Lee |title=With 4 Deaths in Iran and More Cases on 3 Continents, Fears of Coronavirus Pandemic Rise |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/21/world/asia/china-coronavirus-iran.html |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Colombia==\nOn 22 March, about 23 prisoners were killed and 83 injured during a prison riot in [[La Modelo]] in Bogota which erupted amid fears over spreading of the coronavirus through prison walls.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/colombia-coronavirus-23-killed-prison-riot-200323104057561.html|title=Colombia coronavirus: 23 killed in prison riot|website=aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/23/americas/colombia-prison-riots/index.html|title=23 dead in prison riot in Colombia prompted by coronavirus fears, Ministry of Justice says|first=Amir |last=Vera|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> It was evident that prisoners across the country were protesting against the poor health services ever since the outbreak of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-51999594|title=At least 23 killed in Colombia prison unrest|date=2020-03-23|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-23|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe government is planning to release about 10,000 prisoners on the weekend of 4\u20135 April 2020. The release will not apply to individuals who have been convicted of sexual offenses against minors, corruption, or crimes against humanity.<ref>[https://www.infobae.com/america/colombia/2020/04/03/colombia-prepara-una-excarcelacion-masiva-de-presos-por-el-avance-del-coronavirus/ Colombia prepares a massive release of prisoners for the advance of the coronavirus] {{in lang|es}} by Jorge Cantillo, Infobae, retrieved 3 Abr 2020</ref>\n\n==Czech Republic==\nDue to the coronavirus, on March 13, Government Resolution No. 204/2020 Coll. banned family members from visiting relatives in prisons and jails. Defense attorneys are exempted from the bans.<ref name=\"prison visits ban\">https://www.vlada.cz/assets/media-centrum/aktualne/DOC130320-130320_204.pdf</ref>\n\n==Ethiopia==\nOn 25 March, 4,011 prisoners were granted pardon by the [[President of Ethiopia|Ethiopian President]] [[Sahle-Work Zewde]] in an effort to prevent the coronavirus spread. The pardon applies only to prisoners convicted of minor crimes who are serving sentences of up to three years and those who are about to be released.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/26/africa/ethiopia-pardons-4000-prisoners-over-coronavirus/index.html|title=Ethiopia pardons more than 4,000 prisoners to help prevent coronavirus spread|website=cnn.com|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=SahleWorkZewde |author=Sahle-Work Zewde |number=1242936296068141058 |date= 26 March 2020|title=In order to reduce prison overcrowding and prevent the spread of #COVID19, I have, in accordance with article 71/7 of our Constitution, granted pardon to 4011 prisoners convicted of minor crimes serving a sentence up to 3 years and those about to be released. }}</ref>\n\n==France==\nOn 16 March, a detainee died in the [[Fresnes prison]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/faits-divers/mort-d-un-detenu-a-fresnes-les-prisons-a-l-epreuve-de-l-epidemie-de-coronavirus-19-03-2020-8283483.php|title=Mort d'un d\u00e9tenu \u00e0 Fresnes : les prisons \u00e0 l'\u00e9preuve de l'\u00e9pid\u00e9mie de coronavirus|website=leparisien.fr|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\nOn 22 of March a mutiny erupted in the [[Uzerche]] Detention Center where 250 inmates had to be evacuated for unusable cells.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/faits-divers/mutinerie-a-la-prison-d-uzerche-en-correze-22-03-2020-8285724.php|title=Mutinerie \u00e0 la prison d\u2019Uzerche, en Corr\u00e8ze : pr\u00e8s de 250 cellules inutilisables|website=leparisien.fr|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Iran==\nOn March 3, more than 54,000 prisoners were temporarily released to prevent the spread of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51723398 |title=Coronavirus: Iran temporarily frees 54,000 prisoners to combat spread |work=BBC News |date=3 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\nPrisoners rioted in southern Iran on March 30. Since the beginning of the year, riots have broken out in prisons in [[Aligudarz]], [[Hamedan]], and [[Tabriz]], with some prisoners escaping. 70 inmates escaped Saqqez Prison in [[Kurdistan province]] on March 27. 100,000 prisoners have been released as a measure to contain the pandemic, but an estimated 50,000 people are still behind bars, including violent offenders and dual nationals and others with Western ties.<ref name=riot_iran>[https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/jordan-releases-travelers-quarantined-dead-sea-hotels-69867295?cid=clicksource_76_null_headlines_hed Prisoners riot in Iran; Netanyahu goes into self-quarantine] By AMIR VAHDAT and ARON HELLER, Associated Press, 30 March 2020</ref>\n\n==Italy==\nAn investigation was opened after 6 convicts died in the Sant'Anna prison of [[Modena]] from an overdose, other riots emerged in [[San Vittore Prison|San Vittore]] and in the ''La Dogaia'' in [[Prato]] and 80 detainees escaped from [[Foggia]]'s prison amid chaos in prisons sparked by the government new restrictions due to the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.open.online/2020/03/09/coronavirus-rivolta-in-un-carcere-di-modena-morto-un-detenuto/ |title=Caos nelle carceri per il coronavirus, 6 morti a Modena per overdose: aperta indagine. Fiamme a San Vittore e Prato. Fuga dei detenuti a Foggia |work=open.online |date=9 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Mexico==\nA riot in a migrant detention center in [[Tenosique]], Tabasco, Mexico, leaves a Guatemalan man dead and four people injured on 31 March. The detainees were worried about a possible COVID-19 outbreak.<ref>[https://www.informador.mx/mexico/Motin-en-estacion-migratoria-de-Tabasco-deja-un-muerto-y-cuatro-heridos-20200401-0120.html Riot in Tabasco immigration station leaves one dead and four wounded] {{in lang|es}} EFE/Informador, 1 April 2020</ref>\n\n[[Mexico City]] began to sanitize its 13 penitentiaries and four detention centers on 4 April. The number of visitors was cut in half and staff, providers, and inmates will be evaluated for COVID-19. The inmates will also be given [[measles]] shots as the city is experiencing an outbreak of measles at this time. There are 25,243 inmates including 687 elderly prisoners, 488 with disabilities, 188 with HIV, and nine pregnant women.<ref>[https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/metropoli/cdmx/sanitizan-penales-de-cdmx-y-reducen-visitas-por-coronavirus-5059723.html CDMX penalties are sanitized and visits are reduced due to coronavirus] by Israel Zamarr\u00f3n, El Sol de M\u00e9xico, 4 April 2020</ref>\n\n==Somaliland==\n\nPresident [[Muse Bihi Abdi]] pardoned 574 prisoners and ordered them released, in order to control the spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |title=COVID-19: Somaliland releases 574 prisoners |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/africa/covid-19-somaliland-releases-574-prisoners-/1788051 |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=www.aa.com.tr}}</ref>\n\n==Syria==\n{{See also|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Syria}}\n[[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] militants in Hassakeh province in eastern Syria rioted and four escaped from prison. While there are no reports of coronavirus infections in prisons in the area, there are concerns about a possible outbreak in overcrowded facilities. Kurdish authorities run more than two dozen detention facilities in northeastern Syria, holding about 10,000 ISIL fighters, including 2,000 foreigners, 800 of them from Europe.<ref>[https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/militants-riot-eastern-syria-prison-escape-69865276?cid=clicksource_76_null_articleroll_hed IS militants riot in eastern Syria prison, some escape] By The Associated Press/ABC News, 30 March 2020</ref>\n\n==Thailand==\nA riot started at the prison in [[Buriram Province]] in northeastern Thailand on 29 March when a false rumor about coronavirus infection spread as a cover-up for an escape attempt. Seven of the 2,100 prisoners escaped and were recaptured. Two prisoners at a different facility in the country have been diagnosed with Covid-19, and families have been banned from visiting prisons in the country for 14 days.<ref>[https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/riot-breaks-prison-northeast-thailand-69859536?cid=clicksource_76_null_articleroll_hed Coronavirus rumors alleged to have set off Thai prison riot] By The Associated Press/ABC News, 29 March 2020</ref>\n\n==Turkey==\nOn 13 March, Minister of Justice [[Abdulhamit G\u00fcl]] announced that meetings in all open and closed prisons, the use of family meeting rooms and transfers between prisons were delayed for two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/tr/koronavirus/adalet-bakani-gul-acik-ve-kapali-tum-cezaevlerindeki-gorusler-iki-hafta-sureyle-ertelenmistir/1765345|title=Adalet Bakan\u0131 G\u00fcl: A\u00e7\u0131k ve kapal\u0131 t\u00fcm cezaevlerindeki g\u00f6r\u00fc\u015fler iki hafta s\u00fcreyle ertelenmi\u015ftir|date=13 March 2020|publisher=Anadolu Agency|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, the [[Human Rights Association (Turkey)|Human Rights Association]], [[Human Rights Foundation of Turkey]], Association of Lawyers for Liberty, Contemporary Lawyers Association, and Health and Social Service Workers Union of Civil Society in the Penal System, also published a statement on the COVID-19 outbreak and urged for immediate action in prisons. In their article, they emphasized on informing the public, especially family and lawyers of prisoners, about quarantine practices and the health status of prisoners.<ref>[https://tihv.org.tr/covid-19-salgini-ve-hapishanelerde-acilen-alinmasi-gereken-onlemler/ Covid-19 Salg\u0131n\u0131 ve Hapishanelerde Acilen Al\u0131nmas\u0131 Gereken \u00d6nlemler]</ref>\n\n==United Kingdom==\nThe government released specific guidance to prisons in the event of coronavirus symptoms or cases, specifically the rule that \"any prisoner or detainee with a new, continuous cough or a high temperature should be placed in [[protective isolation]] for 7 days\".<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19: prisons and other prescribed places of detention guidance |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-prisons-and-other-prescribed-places-of-detention-guidance/covid-19-prisons-and-other-prescribed-places-of-detention-guidance |website=GOV.UK |accessdate=20 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, the first coronavirus case was reported in a UK prison. The prisoner, who had been serving time in [[HMP Manchester]] (commonly referred to as Strangeways), was moved to a hospital. While no other prisoners or staff tested positive for the virus, thirteen prisoners and four members of staff were put into isolation as a precaution.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bulman |first1=May |title=First UK prisoner infected with coronavirus |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/coronavirus-cases-prison-uk-hmp-manchester-latest-symptoms-a9409251.html |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=The Independent |date=18 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Prison visits remained open, but the situation is being monitored.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Slater |first1=Chris |title=Strangeways prisoner tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/strangeways-prisoner-tests-positive-coronavirus-17944421 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>  \n\nOn 19 March, it was revealed that around 75 officers at [[HMP Berwyn]] in Wales were off work due to sickness or self-isolation, and 22 prisoners showing symptoms of coronavirus were being isolated by the prison. However, the prison had enough staff members to remain fully operational.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rees |first1=Jenny |title=Seventy-five prison officers off sick or isolating |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51966387 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the case in HMP Manchester, public services think tank [[Reform (think tank)|Reform]] called for the release of 2,305 \"low-risk\" offenders on short sentences to reduce the risk of coronavirus on the prison population.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cowburn |first1=Ashley |title=Ministers urged to release hundreds of prisoners on short sentences to combat coronavirus |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-uk-prison-inmates-government-ministers-curfew-a9412661.html |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=The Independent |date=20 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Their report argues that prison are \"overcrowded [with] insanitary conditions and poor-quality healthcare\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Reducing the prison population: Extending Home Detention Curfew and scrapping short sentences {{!}} Reform |url=https://reform.uk/research/reducing-prison-population-extending-home-detention-curfew-and-scrapping-short-sentences |website=reform.uk |accessdate=20 March 2020 |date=March 2020}}</ref> Similar actions have been taken in Iran and the United States.<ref>{{cite news |title=US jails begin releasing prisoners amid pandemic |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-51947802 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, former justice secretary David Gauke called for suspension of short sentences and early release of some prisoners to avoid COVID-19 spread.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/21/prisons-could-see-800-deaths-from-coronavirus-without-protective-measures \"Prisons could see 800 deaths from coronavirus without protective measures,\"] The Guardian, March 21, 2020</ref>\n\n==United States==\nJail and prison officials across the country try to prevent outbreaks of coronavirus in the nation's 6,000 prisons. Between March 22 and March 26, 23 inmates had escaped and at least one inmate had tested positive for Covid-19 in each of two prisons. Judges have ordered the liberation of thousands of prison inmates, and there are calls to release all medically-vulnerable inmates.<ref name=NY>[https://abcnews.go.com/US/releases-infections-fear-us-coronavirus-crisis-jails-prisons/story?id=69803066&cid=referral_taboola_feed Releases, infections, fear: U.S. coronavirus crisis in jails and prisons looms] By Chris Francescani, ABC News, 26 March 2020</ref>\n\nPrevention is complicated by poor sanitation at many prisons. Alcohol-based [[hand sanitizer]] is often prohibited for inmates.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus and Prisons: A Toxic Combination |url=https://www.themarshallproject.org/2020/03/06/when-purell-is-contraband-how-do-you-contain-coronavirus |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Marshall Project |date=6 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Williams |first1=Timothy |last2=Weiser |first2=Benjamin |last3=Rashbaum |first3=William K. |title=\u2018Jails Are Petri Dishes\u2019: Inmates Freed as the Virus Spreads Behind Bars |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/us/coronavirus-prisons-jails.html |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Federal correctional system===\nAttorney General [[William Barr]] announced on March 26, 2020, that he had instructed [[List of United States federal prisons|federal prisons]] to free some inmates to lessen the impact of the coronavirus epidemic. The order favors inmates over 60 who have not been convicted of violent or sex crimes and applies to about 2,000 of the 170,000 inmates in the federal correctional system. The majority of the 2.2 million prisoners in the United States are in state or local custody. There have been about a dozen cases of Covid-19 among federal prisoners and staff.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/us-free-prisoners-amid-coronavirus-threat-221836923.html U.S. to free some prisoners amid coronavirus threat] AFP, 26 March 2020</ref>\n\nPatrick Jones, a 47-year old inmate at a minimum-security prison in [[Oakdale, Louisiana]] became the first fatality of Covid-19 in a federal prison on March 29. Five other inmates are infected.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/inmate-dies-contracting-coronavirus-louisiana-150800571.html Inmate dies after contracting coronavirus at Louisiana federal prison] by Rich Schapiro, NBC News, 29 March 2020</ref> The federal [[Bureau of Prisons]] is locking all its 146,000 inmates in their cells from April 1 to 14. The situation has become so bad at [[Federal Correctional Complex, Oakdale]] in Louisiana that authorities have stopped testing for COVID-19 and instead assume that anyone with symptoms is infected.<ref>[https://apnews.com/c6c546586b9d3769b10ce2ab2bffbbdc Federal inmates to be locked in cells for 14 days amid virus] AP, 31 March 2020</ref>\n\n===Immigration facilities===\nDetainees at several [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement|U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE)]] facilities went on strike to demand sanitary supplies.<ref>[https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/coronavirus-fears-spark-prison-unrest-worldwide.html Coronavirus Fears Spark Prison Strikes, Protests, and Riots Around the World]</ref> Federal judges in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in California|California]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania]] have ordered ICE to release several detainees who have sued. Lawsuits are pending in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maryland|Maryland]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Massachusetts|Massachusetts]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Jersey|New Jersey]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania]], and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington (state)|Washington state]]. As of April 2, there were 35,000 people in ICE custody.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/judge-maryland-weighs-release-2-204159304.html Judge in Maryland weighs release of 2 detained immigrants] by MICHAEL KUNZELMAN, Associated Press, 2 April 2020</ref>\n\n===Arizona===\nOn March 21, it was reported that 50 inmates have been released in Coconino County in a state to reduce coronavirus risks. In Pima County, the sheriff proposed measures to reduce the inmate population, such as releasing 135 people jailed for probation violations or relocating some prisoners to state prisons.<ref>Jacques Billeaud, [https://www.azfamily.com/news/some-sheriffs-ask-to-reduce-jail-population-amid-virus-worry/article_3ce6087c-6b97-11ea-ae88-bf7649a07544.html \"Some sheriffs ask to reduce jail population amid virus worry,\"] azfamily.com, March 21, 2020</ref>\n\n===California===\n\n* '''Alameda County:''' On March 20, Alameda County officials announced that 247 people would be released from Santa Rita Jail, located in Dublin.<ref name=lat>Marua Dolan, Alene Tchekmedyian, Piage St. John, [https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-03-20/california-releases-more-jail-inmates-amid-coronavirus-crisis \"California releases more jail inmates amid coronavirus crisis,\"] Los Angeles Times, March 20, 2020</ref>\n* '''Los Angeles County:''' On March 17, the county Sheriff's Department announced that it had reduced the inmate population by 600 during the previous two weeks in an attempt to keep prisoners from coronavirus.<ref name=bbc/>\n* '''San Diego County:''' On March 16, the Sheriff's Department said it had started reducing the number of people being accepted into the county's seven jails and had received approval for early release of some prisoners. Other measures included in-cell meals, a suspension of visitation, and suspension of jail programs.<ref>Teri Figueroa, Karen Kucher, [https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/public-safety/story/2020-03-16/jails-to-release-some-inmates-adjust-booking-criteria-amid-coronavirus-concerns \"Jails to release some inmates, adjust booking criteria amid coronavirus concerns,\"] San Diego Union-Tribune, March 16, 2020.</ref>\n\n===Georgia===\nThe [[Georgia Department of Corrections]] (DOC) suspended visitations and announced additional sanitation measures, but the ''Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' reported that inmates had seen no extra soap.<ref name=\"covid-ga-doc-prisons\">{{cite web |last1=Boone |first1=Christian |last2=Sharpe |first2=Joshua |title='No extra soap': Georgia inmates say prisons not ready for COVID-19 |url=https://www.ajc.com/news/crime--law/inmates-say-state-federal-prisons-ill-prepared-for-covid/JPgQovDI7tvdY3Jmh6vwvK/ |publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> A prison worker was confirmed to have the coronavirus on March 18 \u2014 the DOC, citing \"security and [[HIPAA]] restrictions\", declining to name the affected prison. The first detected case on COVID-19 in a prison inmate was at [[Lee State Prison]] two days later, on March 20.<ref name=\"prison-covid-positive-03-20\">{{cite web |last1=Blau |first1=Max |last2=Sharpe |first2=Joshua |title=NEW FINDINGS: Georgia prison inmate tests positive for COVID-19 |url=https://www.ajc.com/news/local/breaking-georgia-prison-inmate-tests-positive-for-covid/2U3hE09fRS6WG9SMHOYZ7I/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, CNN reported that three inmates tested positive for coronavirus at [[Lee State Prison]] in [[Leesburg, Georgia|Leesburg]]. Three other prisoners were under observation with similar symptoms.<ref>Faith Karimi, [https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/21/health/georgia-inmates-coronavirus/index.html \"Three inmates test positive for coronavirus in Georgia as concerns grow over unprepared prison system,\"] CNN Health, March 21, 2020</ref>\n\n===Illinois===\nTesting for COVID-19 disclosed the first case of infection on March 22 in [[Cook County Jail]] in Chicago. 10% of the 5,000 inmates were released as a cautionary measure, but the number of infections had risen to 134 by March 30. Fifteen inmates and eleven staff have tested positive at other facilities in the state, with at least 80 waiting for test results. One prisoner died on March 30 at [[Stateville Correctional Center]] in [[Crest Hill, Illinois]].<ref>[https://wgntv.com/news/coronavirus/concerns-grow-at-cook-county-jail-as-covid-19-spreads/ Concerns grow at Cook County Jail as COVID-19 spreads] by Mike Lowe, WGN-TV 9, 30 March 2020</ref> \n\n===Massachusetts===\nThe first prison case of COVID-19 in Massachusetts was reported on March 21 at [[Massachusetts Treatment Center]]. The prisoner and his roommate were placed in quarantine on March 19.<ref>[https://www.wwlp.com/news/health/coronavirus-local-impact/first-case-of-covid-19-in-bridgewater-prison/ \"First case of COVID-19 in Bridgewater Prison,\"] Channel 22 News, March 21, 2020</ref> As of March 31, 17 prisoners had tested positive at the Massachusetts Treatment Center as well as six Department of Correction staff \u2013 four at the treatment center, one at [[Massachusetts Correctional Institution \u2013 Shirley|MCI-Shirley]], and one at the Department of Correction central office. Two prisoners have tested positive at the Middlesex Jail & House of Correction in Billerica, MA, as have 14 employees in the state's county jail systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wgbh.org/news/local-news/2020/03/30/arguments-at-sjc-tuesday-over-petition-to-reduce-prison-populations-due-to-pandemic|title=Arguments At SJC Tuesday Over Petition To Reduce Prison Populations Due To Pandemic|last=|first=|date=|website=|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n===Michigan===\nThe [[Michigan Department of Corrections]] banned visitors to prisons, along with prohibiting any volunteers from the prison. Staff at prisons will be required to have their temperature tested and be proven to be under {{cvt|100.4|\u00b0F}} along with other measures.<ref>[https://www.michigan.gov/coronavirus/0,9753,7-406-98163-521571--,00.html MDOC Halts All Visits at State Prisons] Michigan.gov</ref>  The [[Michigan Career and Technical Institute]] suspended all programs until April 5.<ref>[https://www.michigan.gov/coronavirus/0,9753,7-406-98163-521668--,00.html Michigan Career & Technical Institute to Close to Protect Against COVID-19] Michigan.gov</ref>\n\n===New Jersey===\nOn March 24, a 31-year-old male Mexican national in custody by [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement|U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE)]] in [[Hackensack, New Jersey]] was held in isolation after being tested positive for Covid-19. He was the first migrant to test positive, and ICE suspended the intake of new migrants.<ref>[https://www.fox44news.com/news/mexican-man-becomes-1st-in-immigration-detention-to-test-positive-for-covid-19/ Mexican man becomes 1st in immigration detention to test positive for COVID-19] Fox 44 News/AP, 24 March 2020, retrieved 26 March 2020</ref>\n\n===New York===\nAfter a guard and a prisoner tested positive for coronavirus at [[Rikers Island]] prison, New York City Mayor Bill de Blasio said that city officials will identify individuals for release, including persons arrested for minor crimes and those most vulnerable to infection due to chronic health problems. In addition to the cases at Rikers, other prisons in the state, including [[Sing Sing]], have recorded positive tests among prisoners, and one member of the correction's department has died from the virus.<ref name=bbc>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51947802 \"US jails begin releasing prisoners to stem Covid-19 infections,\"] BBC News, March 19, 2020</ref>\n\nAs of March 25, 75 New York City inmates have tested positive for Covid-19 and 37 city corrections staff members, up from 50 inmates and 30 staffers the previous day. City jails are notoriously crowded, with beds often touching and in at least one instance, 29 people share a single toilet.<ref name=NY></ref>\n\n===Pennsylvania===\nDue to ongoing public health concerns related to the coronavirus, on March 13, [[Eastern State Penitentiary]] (a historic site which stopped operating as a prison in 1971) was closed to the public.<ref>[https://www.easternstate.org/ Eastern State Penitentiary,\"] accessed March 21, 2020</ref>\n\n===South Dakota===\nNine prisoners escaped from a minimal-security women's prison on March 23, the same day a fellow-inmate tested positive for Covid-19. Three were captured on the [[Crow Creek Indian Reservation]] and one was captured in [[Rapid City, South Dakota|Rapid City]]. It was not immediately clear if the diagnosis prompted the prisoners to run.<ref name=SD>[https://abcnews.go.com/US/inmates-bolt-south-dakota-prison-day-prisoner-tested/story?id=69789196 9 inmates bolt from South Dakota prison on same day a prisoner tested positive for coronavirus] By Bill Hutchinson, ABC News, 25 March 2020</ref>\n\n===Washington state===\nFourteen inmates escaped from the county jail in [[Yakima County, Washington|Yakima County]] on March 23. They used a table to break down an exit door and then climbed a fence. The U.S. Marshals Service offered rewards of up to $1,000 for information leading to the arrests of the escaped inmates.<ref name=SD></ref>\n\n===Wisconsin===\nThe first COVID-19 positive case in the Wisconsin state prison system, an employee at [[Waupun Correctional Institution]], was reported on March 18 by warden Brian Foster. Inmate advocacy groups called on the Department of Corrections and Governor [[Tony Evers]] to change prison policies to protect prisoners and guards during the epidemic.<ref>Emily Hamer, [https://madison.com/wsj/news/local/wisconsin-prison-employee-tests-positive-for-covid--inmate-advocates/article_724c81a5-61e8-5bb2-b5ac-24ba210a9a76.html \"Wisconsin prison employee tests positive for COVID-19; inmate advocates call for protections amid pandemic,\"] State Journal, March 20, 2020</ref>\n\n==Venezuela==\n''[[Reuters]]'' reported that Venezuela's notoriously overcrowded and unsanitary prisons could spread the coronavirus \"like a fast-moving fire.\" Venezuelan prisons frequently lack bathrooms, people sleep on floors, and many inmates spend their days without shirts or shoes on, in part to combat the infernal heat of windowless facilities.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ellsworth|first=Brian|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-prisons/overcrowded-and-unsanitary-venezuelas-prisons-brace-for-coronavirus-idUSKBN215323|title=Overcrowded and unsanitary, Venezuela's prisons brace for coronavirus|date=18 March 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live|last2=Sequera|first2=Vivian}}</ref> \n\nThis has caused [[United States Secretary of State|US Secretary of State]] [[Mike Pompeo]] to demand the Maduro government release six [[Citgo]] executives, held in prison since 2017, on humanitarian grounds.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=SecPompeo|number=1240617609441280002|date=19 March 2020|title=It is past time for the Maduro regime to release the #Citgo6 who are currently languishing in the notorious Helicoide prison in #Venezuela. 2+ years in prison with no evidence brought against them; 18 hearings cancelled. Unacceptable.|author=Secretary Pompeo}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" /> Pompeo said that all six men have weakened [[immune system]]s and \"face a grave health risk if they become infected\" with the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200319-us-demands-venezuela-free-citgo-executives-as-virus-hits|title=US demands Venezuela free Citgo executives as virus hits|date=19 March 2020|work=[[France 24]]|access-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live|agency=[[Agence France-Presse]]}}</ref> The Venezuelan Medical Federation asked for the release of the political prisoners in the country, specifically [[Roberto Marrero]], [[Juan Requesens]] and other lawmakers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lapatilla.com/2020/03/14/presidente-de-la-fmv-exhorta-a-que-se-liberen-a-presos-politicos-por-coronavirus/|title=Presidente de la FMV exhorta a que se liberen a presos pol\u00edticos por coronavirus|first=|date=14 March 2020|website=[[La Patilla]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, 84 out of 518 inmates escaped from a prison in San Carlos, [[Zulia]], after restrictions against the pandemic were announced, including jail visits. Mayor Bladimir Labrador declared that ten prisoners were killed during the prison break and that two policemen were detained for complicity. According to Carlos Nieto Palma from the NGO Ventana a la Libertad, the suspension of visits directly affects the prisoner's nutrition, given that there was no state-sponsored program to feed them.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.es/internacional/2020/03/19/5e72c06f21efa09a6a8b462a.html|title=Las restricciones por el coronavirus provocan una fuga de presos que deja 10 muertos en Venezuela|date=19 March 2020|website=[[El Mundo (Venezuela)|El Mundo]]|publisher=AFP|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The NGO Provea denounced \"grave human rights violations\" after a military spokesperson announced the \"neutralization\" of 35 escapees.  State authorities later declared that the there were eight deaths.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://talcualdigital.com/provea-denuncia-asesinato-de-35-presos-fugados-de-reten-en-zulia/|title=Provea denuncia asesinato de 35 presos fugados de ret\u00e9n en Zulia|last=|first=|date=18 March 2020|website=[[Tal Cual]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Prisons]]\n[[Category:Prison healthcare]]\n", "text_old": "{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] has impacted prisons''' around the world.\n\n==Afghanistan==\nThe Afghan government released 10,000 prisoners, mostly women, young people, the critically ill, and inmates over 55 on March 26, 2020.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/afghanistan-release-10-000-prisoners-slow-coronavirus-spread-211850224.html Afghanistan to release up to 10,000 prisoners to slow coronavirus spread] AFP, 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n==Australia==\nOn 16 March, the ACT government declared a public health emergency.{{cn|date=March 2020}} It has also planned to cancel all visits to the [[Alexander Maconochie Centre|Alexander Maconochie]] prison from March 23. ACT Corrective Services Commissioner Jon Peach stated that as a result there would be \"increased access to telephones\" for prisoners to keep in touch with their families.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-21/canberra-records-new-cases-of-covid-19-prison-visits-stopped/12077734|title=Canberra coronavirus cases increase as Health Minister halts prison visits|publisher=ABC News|date=21 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Brazil==\n\nHundreds of prisoners (who work outside the prison during the day) escaped from four prisons in [[S\u00e3o Paulo state]] after visitors were restricted and Easter furloughs were cancelled due to health concerns.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/17/come-back-monday-ok-hundreds-of-prisoners-escape-in-brazil-amid-covid-19-anger 'Come back Monday, OK?' Hundreds of prisoners escape in Brazil amid Covid-19 anger]</ref>\n\n==China==\n\nThe virus spread in at least four prisons in China.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Vivian |last2=McNeil Jr |first2=Donald G. |last3=Fassihi |first3=Farnaz |last4=Myers |first4=Steven Lee |title=With 4 Deaths in Iran and More Cases on 3 Continents, Fears of Coronavirus Pandemic Rise |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/21/world/asia/china-coronavirus-iran.html |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Colombia==\nOn 22 March, about 23 prisoners were killed and 83 injured during a prison riot in [[La Modelo]] in Bogota which erupted amid fears over spreading of the coronavirus through prison walls.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/colombia-coronavirus-23-killed-prison-riot-200323104057561.html|title=Colombia coronavirus: 23 killed in prison riot|website=aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/23/americas/colombia-prison-riots/index.html|title=23 dead in prison riot in Colombia prompted by coronavirus fears, Ministry of Justice says|first=Amir |last=Vera|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> It was evident that prisoners across the country were protesting against the poor health services ever since the outbreak of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-51999594|title=At least 23 killed in Colombia prison unrest|date=2020-03-23|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-23|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe government is planning to release about 10,000 prisoners on the weekend of 4\u20135 April 2020. The release will not apply to individuals who have been convicted of sexual offenses against minors, corruption, or crimes against humanity.<ref>[https://www.infobae.com/america/colombia/2020/04/03/colombia-prepara-una-excarcelacion-masiva-de-presos-por-el-avance-del-coronavirus/ Colombia prepares a massive release of prisoners for the advance of the coronavirus] {{in lang|es}} by Jorge Cantillo, Infobae, retrieved 3 Abr 2020</ref>\n\n==Czech Republic==\nDue to the coronavirus, on March 13, Government Resolution No. 204/2020 Coll. banned family members from visiting relatives in prisons and jails. Defense attorneys are exempted from the bans.<ref name=\"prison visits ban\">https://www.vlada.cz/assets/media-centrum/aktualne/DOC130320-130320_204.pdf</ref>\n\n==Ethiopia==\nOn 25 March, 4,011 prisoners were granted pardon by the [[President of Ethiopia|Ethiopian President]] [[Sahle-Work Zewde]] in an effort to prevent the coronavirus spread. The pardon applies only to prisoners convicted of minor crimes who are serving sentences of up to three years and those who are about to be released.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/26/africa/ethiopia-pardons-4000-prisoners-over-coronavirus/index.html|title=Ethiopia pardons more than 4,000 prisoners to help prevent coronavirus spread|website=cnn.com|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=SahleWorkZewde |author=Sahle-Work Zewde |number=1242936296068141058 |date= 26 March 2020|title=In order to reduce prison overcrowding and prevent the spread of #COVID19, I have, in accordance with article 71/7 of our Constitution, granted pardon to 4011 prisoners convicted of minor crimes serving a sentence up to 3 years and those about to be released. }}</ref>\n\n==France==\nOn 16 March, a detainee died in the [[Fresnes prison]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/faits-divers/mort-d-un-detenu-a-fresnes-les-prisons-a-l-epreuve-de-l-epidemie-de-coronavirus-19-03-2020-8283483.php|title=Mort d'un d\u00e9tenu \u00e0 Fresnes : les prisons \u00e0 l'\u00e9preuve de l'\u00e9pid\u00e9mie de coronavirus|website=leparisien.fr|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\nOn 22 of March a mutiny erupted in the [[Uzerche]] Detention Center where 250 inmates had to be evacuated for unusable cells.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/faits-divers/mutinerie-a-la-prison-d-uzerche-en-correze-22-03-2020-8285724.php|title=Mutinerie \u00e0 la prison d\u2019Uzerche, en Corr\u00e8ze : pr\u00e8s de 250 cellules inutilisables|website=leparisien.fr|access-date=2020-04-9}}</ref>\n\n==Iran==\nOn March 3, more than 54,000 prisoners were temporarily released to prevent the spread of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51723398 |title=Coronavirus: Iran temporarily frees 54,000 prisoners to combat spread |work=BBC News |date=3 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\nPrisoners rioted in southern Iran on March 30. Since the beginning of the year, riots have broken out in prisons in [[Aligudarz]], [[Hamedan]], and [[Tabriz]], with some prisoners escaping. 70 inmates escaped Saqqez Prison in [[Kurdistan province]] on March 27. 100,000 prisoners have been released as a measure to contain the pandemic, but an estimated 50,000 people are still behind bars, including violent offenders and dual nationals and others with Western ties.<ref name=riot_iran>[https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/jordan-releases-travelers-quarantined-dead-sea-hotels-69867295?cid=clicksource_76_null_headlines_hed Prisoners riot in Iran; Netanyahu goes into self-quarantine] By AMIR VAHDAT and ARON HELLER, Associated Press, 30 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n==Italy==\nAn investigation was opened after 6 convicts died in the Sant'Anna prison of [[Modena]] from an overdose, other riots emerged in [[San Vittore Prison|San Vittore]] and in the ''La Dogaia'' in [[Prato]] and 80 detainees escaped from [[Foggia]]'s prison amid chaos in prisons sparked by the government new restrictions due to the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.open.online/2020/03/09/coronavirus-rivolta-in-un-carcere-di-modena-morto-un-detenuto/ |title=Caos nelle carceri per il coronavirus, 6 morti a Modena per overdose: aperta indagine. Fiamme a San Vittore e Prato. Fuga dei detenuti a Foggia |work=open.online |date=9 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Mexico==\nA riot in a migrant detention center in [[Tenosique]], Tabasco, Mexico, leaves a Guatemalan man dead and four people injured on 31 March. The detainees were worried about a possible COVID-19 outbreak.<ref>[https://www.informador.mx/mexico/Motin-en-estacion-migratoria-de-Tabasco-deja-un-muerto-y-cuatro-heridos-20200401-0120.html Riot in Tabasco immigration station leaves one dead and four wounded] {{in lang|es}} EFE/Informador, 1 April 2020</ref>\n\n[[Mexico City]] began to sanitize its 13 penitentiaries and four detention centers on 4 April. The number of visitors was cut in half and staff, providers, and inmates will be evaluated for COVID-19. The inmates will also be given [[measles]] shots as the city is experiencing an outbreak of measles at this time. There are 25,243 inmates including 687 elderly prisoners, 488 with disabilities, 188 with HIV, and nine pregnant women.<ref>[https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/metropoli/cdmx/sanitizan-penales-de-cdmx-y-reducen-visitas-por-coronavirus-5059723.html CDMX penalties are sanitized and visits are reduced due to coronavirus] by Israel Zamarr\u00f3n, El Sol de M\u00e9xico, 4 Apr 2020</ref>\n\n==Somaliland==\n\nPresident [[Muse Bihi Abdi]] pardoned 574 prisoners and ordered them released, in order to control the spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |title=COVID-19: Somaliland releases 574 prisoners |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/africa/covid-19-somaliland-releases-574-prisoners-/1788051 |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=www.aa.com.tr}}</ref>\n\n==Syria==\n{{See also|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Syria}}\n[[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] militants in Hassakeh province in eastern Syria rioted and four escaped from prison. While there are no reports of coronavirus infections in prisons in the area, there are concerns about a possible outbreak in overcrowded facilities. Kurdish authorities run more than two dozen detention facilities in northeastern Syria, holding about 10,000 ISIL fighters, including 2,000 foreigners, 800 of them from Europe.<ref>[https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/militants-riot-eastern-syria-prison-escape-69865276?cid=clicksource_76_null_articleroll_hed IS militants riot in eastern Syria prison, some escape] By The Associated Press/ABC News, 30 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n==Thailand==\nA riot started at the prison in [[Buriram Province]] in northeastern Thailand on 29 March when a false rumor about coronavirus infection spread as a cover-up for an escape attempt. Seven of the 2,100 prisoners escaped and were recaptured. Two prisoners at a different facility in the country have been diagnosed with Covid-19, and families have been banned from visiting prisons in the country for 14 days.<ref>[https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/riot-breaks-prison-northeast-thailand-69859536?cid=clicksource_76_null_articleroll_hed Coronavirus rumors alleged to have set off Thai prison riot] By The Associated Press/ABC News, 29 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n==Turkey==\nOn 13 March, Minister of Justice [[Abdulhamit G\u00fcl]] announced that meetings in all open and closed prisons, the use of family meeting rooms and transfers between prisons were delayed for two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/tr/koronavirus/adalet-bakani-gul-acik-ve-kapali-tum-cezaevlerindeki-gorusler-iki-hafta-sureyle-ertelenmistir/1765345|title=Adalet Bakan\u0131 G\u00fcl: A\u00e7\u0131k ve kapal\u0131 t\u00fcm cezaevlerindeki g\u00f6r\u00fc\u015fler iki hafta s\u00fcreyle ertelenmi\u015ftir|date=13 March 2020|publisher=Anadolu Agency|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, the [[Human Rights Association (Turkey)|Human Rights Association]], [[Human Rights Foundation of Turkey]], Association of Lawyers for Liberty, Contemporary Lawyers Association, and Health and Social Service Workers Union of Civil Society in the Penal System, also published a statement on the COVID-19 outbreak and urged for immediate action in prisons. In their article, they emphasized on informing the public, especially family and lawyers of prisoners, about quarantine practices and the health status of prisoners.<ref>[https://tihv.org.tr/covid-19-salgini-ve-hapishanelerde-acilen-alinmasi-gereken-onlemler/ Covid-19 Salg\u0131n\u0131 ve Hapishanelerde Acilen Al\u0131nmas\u0131 Gereken \u00d6nlemler]</ref>\n\n==United Kingdom==\nThe government released specific guidance to prisons in the event of coronavirus symptoms or cases, specifically the rule that \"any prisoner or detainee with a new, continuous cough or a high temperature should be placed in [[protective isolation]] for 7 days\".<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19: prisons and other prescribed places of detention guidance |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-prisons-and-other-prescribed-places-of-detention-guidance/covid-19-prisons-and-other-prescribed-places-of-detention-guidance |website=GOV.UK |accessdate=20 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, the first coronavirus case was reported in a UK prison. The prisoner, who had been serving time in [[HMP Manchester]] (commonly referred to as Strangeways), was moved to a hospital. While no other prisoners or staff tested positive for the virus, thirteen prisoners and four members of staff were put into isolation as a precaution.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bulman |first1=May |title=First UK prisoner infected with coronavirus |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/coronavirus-cases-prison-uk-hmp-manchester-latest-symptoms-a9409251.html |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=The Independent |date=18 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Prison visits remained open, but the situation is being monitored.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Slater |first1=Chris |title=Strangeways prisoner tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/strangeways-prisoner-tests-positive-coronavirus-17944421 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>  \n\nOn 19 March, it was revealed that around 75 officers at [[HMP Berwyn]] in Wales were off work due to sickness or self-isolation, and 22 prisoners showing symptoms of coronavirus were being isolated by the prison. However, the prison had enough staff members to remain fully operational.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rees |first1=Jenny |title=Seventy-five prison officers off sick or isolating |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51966387 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the case in HMP Manchester, public services think tank [[Reform (think tank)|Reform]] called for the release of 2,305 \"low-risk\" offenders on short sentences to reduce the risk of coronavirus on the prison population.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cowburn |first1=Ashley |title=Ministers urged to release hundreds of prisoners on short sentences to combat coronavirus |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-uk-prison-inmates-government-ministers-curfew-a9412661.html |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=The Independent |date=20 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Their report argues that prison are \"overcrowded [with] insanitary conditions and poor-quality healthcare\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Reducing the prison population: Extending Home Detention Curfew and scrapping short sentences {{!}} Reform |url=https://reform.uk/research/reducing-prison-population-extending-home-detention-curfew-and-scrapping-short-sentences |website=reform.uk |accessdate=20 March 2020 |date=March 2020}}</ref> Similar actions have been taken in Iran and the United States.<ref>{{cite news |title=US jails begin releasing prisoners amid pandemic |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-51947802 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, former justice secretary David Gauke called for suspension of short sentences and early release of some prisoners to avoid COVID-19 spread.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/21/prisons-could-see-800-deaths-from-coronavirus-without-protective-measures \"Prisons could see 800 deaths from coronavirus without protective measures,\"] The Guardian, March 21, 2020</ref>\n\n==United States==\nJail and prison officials across the country try to prevent outbreaks of coronavirus in the nation's 6,000 prisons. Between March 22 and March 26, 23 inmates had escaped and at least one inmate had tested positive for Covid-19 in each of two prisons. Judges have ordered the liberation of thousands of prison inmates, and there are calls to release all medically-vulnerable inmates.<ref name=NY>[https://abcnews.go.com/US/releases-infections-fear-us-coronavirus-crisis-jails-prisons/story?id=69803066&cid=referral_taboola_feed Releases, infections, fear: U.S. coronavirus crisis in jails and prisons looms] By Chris Francescani, ABC News, 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nPrevention is complicated by poor sanitation at many prisons. Alcohol-based [[hand sanitizer]] is often prohibited for inmates.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus and Prisons: A Toxic Combination |url=https://www.themarshallproject.org/2020/03/06/when-purell-is-contraband-how-do-you-contain-coronavirus |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Marshall Project |date=6 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Williams |first1=Timothy |last2=Weiser |first2=Benjamin |last3=Rashbaum |first3=William K. |title=\u2018Jails Are Petri Dishes\u2019: Inmates Freed as the Virus Spreads Behind Bars |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/us/coronavirus-prisons-jails.html |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Federal correctional system===\nAttorney General [[William Barr]] announced on March 26, 2020, that he had instructed [[List of United States federal prisons|federal prisons]] to free some inmates to lessen the impact of the coronavirus epidemic. The order favors inmates over 60 who have not been convicted of violent or sex crimes and applies to about 2,000 of the 170,000 inmates in the federal correctional system. The majority of the 2.2 million prisoners in the United States are in state or local custody. There have been about a dozen cases of Covid-19 among federal prisoners and staff.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/us-free-prisoners-amid-coronavirus-threat-221836923.html U.S. to free some prisoners amid coronavirus threat] AFP, 26 March 2020</ref>\n\nPatrick Jones, a 47-year old inmate at a minimum-security prison in [[Oakdale, Louisiana]] became the first fatality of Covid-19 in a federal prison on March 29. Five other inmates are infected.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/inmate-dies-contracting-coronavirus-louisiana-150800571.html Inmate dies after contracting coronavirus at Louisiana federal prison] by Rich Schapiro, NBC News, 29 Mar 2020</ref> The federal [[Bureau of Prisons]] is locking all its 146,000 inmates in their cells from April 1 to 14. The situation has become so bad at [[Federal Correctional Complex, Oakdale]] in Louisiana that authorities have stopped testing for COVID-19 and instead assume that anyone with symptoms is infected.<ref>[https://apnews.com/c6c546586b9d3769b10ce2ab2bffbbdc Federal inmates to be locked in cells for 14 days amid virus] AP, 31 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n===Immigration facilities===\nDetainees at several [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement|U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE)]] facilities went on strike to demand sanitary supplies.<ref>[https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/coronavirus-fears-spark-prison-unrest-worldwide.html Coronavirus Fears Spark Prison Strikes, Protests, and Riots Around the World]</ref> Federal judges in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in California|California]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania]] have ordered ICE to release several detainees who have sued. Lawsuits are pending in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maryland|Maryland]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Massachusetts|Massachusetts]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Jersey|New Jersey]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania]], and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington (state)|Washington state]]. As of April 2, there were 35,000 people in ICE custody.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/judge-maryland-weighs-release-2-204159304.html Judge in Maryland weighs release of 2 detained immigrants] by MICHAEL KUNZELMAN, Associated Press, 2 Apr 2020</ref>\n\n===Arizona===\nOn March 21, it was reported that 50 inmates have been released in Coconino County in a state to reduce coronavirus risks. In Pima County, the sheriff proposed measures to reduce the inmate population, such as releasing 135 people jailed for probation violations or relocating some prisoners to state prisons.<ref>Jacques Billeaud, [https://www.azfamily.com/news/some-sheriffs-ask-to-reduce-jail-population-amid-virus-worry/article_3ce6087c-6b97-11ea-ae88-bf7649a07544.html \"Some sheriffs ask to reduce jail population amid virus worry,\"] azfamily.com, March 21, 2020</ref>\n\n===California===\n\n* '''Alameda County:''' On March 20, Alameda County officials announced that 247 people would be released from Santa Rita Jail, located in Dublin.<ref name=lat>Marua Dolan, Alene Tchekmedyian, Piage St. John, [https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-03-20/california-releases-more-jail-inmates-amid-coronavirus-crisis \"California releases more jail inmates amid coronavirus crisis,\"] Los Angeles Times, March 20, 2020</ref>\n* '''Los Angeles County:''' On March 17, the county Sheriff's Department announced that it had reduced the inmate population by 600 during the previous two weeks in an attempt to keep prisoners from coronavirus.<ref name=bbc/>\n* '''San Diego County:''' On March 16, the Sheriff's Department said it had started reducing the number of people being accepted into the county's seven jails and had received approval for early release of some prisoners. Other measures included in-cell meals, a suspension of visitation, and suspension of jail programs.<ref>Teri Figueroa, Karen Kucher, [https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/public-safety/story/2020-03-16/jails-to-release-some-inmates-adjust-booking-criteria-amid-coronavirus-concerns \"Jails to release some inmates, adjust booking criteria amid coronavirus concerns,\"] San Diego Union-Tribune, March 16, 2020.</ref>\n\n===Georgia===\nThe [[Georgia Department of Corrections]] (DOC) suspended visitations and announced additional sanitation measures, but the ''Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' reported that inmates had seen no extra soap.<ref name=\"covid-ga-doc-prisons\">{{cite web |last1=Boone |first1=Christian |last2=Sharpe |first2=Joshua |title='No extra soap': Georgia inmates say prisons not ready for COVID-19 |url=https://www.ajc.com/news/crime--law/inmates-say-state-federal-prisons-ill-prepared-for-covid/JPgQovDI7tvdY3Jmh6vwvK/ |publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> A prison worker was confirmed to have the coronavirus on March 18 \u2014 the DOC, citing \"security and [[HIPAA]] restrictions\", declining to name the affected prison. The first detected case on COVID-19 in a prison inmate was at [[Lee State Prison]] two days later, on March 20.<ref name=\"prison-covid-positive-03-20\">{{cite web |last1=Blau |first1=Max |last2=Sharpe |first2=Joshua |title=NEW FINDINGS: Georgia prison inmate tests positive for COVID-19 |url=https://www.ajc.com/news/local/breaking-georgia-prison-inmate-tests-positive-for-covid/2U3hE09fRS6WG9SMHOYZ7I/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, CNN reported that three inmates tested positive for coronavirus at [[Lee State Prison]] in [[Leesburg, Georgia|Leesburg]]. Three other prisoners were under observation with similar symptoms.<ref>Faith Karimi, [https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/21/health/georgia-inmates-coronavirus/index.html \"Three inmates test positive for coronavirus in Georgia as concerns grow over unprepared prison system,\"] CNN Health, March 21, 2020</ref>\n\n===Illinois===\nTesting for COVID-19 disclosed the first case of infection on March 22 in [[Cook County Jail]] in Chicago. 10% of the 5,000 inmates were released as a cautionary measure, but the number of infections had risen to 134 by March 30. Fifteen inmates and eleven staff have tested positive at other facilities in the state, with at least 80 waiting for test results. One prisoner died on March 30 at [[Stateville Correctional Center]] in [[Crest Hill, Illinois]].<ref>[https://wgntv.com/news/coronavirus/concerns-grow-at-cook-county-jail-as-covid-19-spreads/ Concerns grow at Cook County Jail as COVID-19 spreads] by Mike Lowe, WGN-TV 9, 30 Mar 2020</ref> \n\n===Massachusetts===\nThe first prison case of COVID-19 in Massachusetts was reported on March 21 at [[Massachusetts Treatment Center]]. The prisoner and his roommate were placed in quarantine on March 19.<ref>[https://www.wwlp.com/news/health/coronavirus-local-impact/first-case-of-covid-19-in-bridgewater-prison/ \"First case of COVID-19 in Bridgewater Prison,\"] Channel 22 News, March 21, 2020</ref> As of March 31, 17 prisoners had tested positive at the Massachusetts Treatment Center as well as six Department of Correction staff \u2013 four at the treatment center, one at [[Massachusetts Correctional Institution \u2013 Shirley|MCI-Shirley]], and one at the Department of Correction central office. Two prisoners have tested positive at the Middlesex Jail & House of Correction in Billerica, MA, as have 14 employees in the state's county jail systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wgbh.org/news/local-news/2020/03/30/arguments-at-sjc-tuesday-over-petition-to-reduce-prison-populations-due-to-pandemic|title=Arguments At SJC Tuesday Over Petition To Reduce Prison Populations Due To Pandemic|last=|first=|date=|website=|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n===Michigan===\nThe [[Michigan Department of Corrections]] banned visitors to prisons, along with prohibiting any volunteers from the prison. Staff at prisons will be required to have their temperature tested and be proven to be under {{cvt|100.4|\u00b0F}} along with other measures.<ref>[https://www.michigan.gov/coronavirus/0,9753,7-406-98163-521571--,00.html MDOC Halts All Visits at State Prisons] Michigan.gov</ref>  The [[Michigan Career and Technical Institute]] suspended all programs until April 5.<ref>[https://www.michigan.gov/coronavirus/0,9753,7-406-98163-521668--,00.html Michigan Career & Technical Institute to Close to Protect Against COVID-19] Michigan.gov</ref>\n\n===New Jersey===\nOn March 24, a 31-year-old male Mexican national in custody by [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement|U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE)]] in [[Hackensack, New Jersey]] was held in isolation after being tested positive for Covid-19. He was the first migrant to test positive, and ICE suspended the intake of new migrants.<ref>[https://www.fox44news.com/news/mexican-man-becomes-1st-in-immigration-detention-to-test-positive-for-covid-19/ Mexican man becomes 1st in immigration detention to test positive for COVID-19] Fox 44 News/AP, 24 Mar 2020, retrieved 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n===New York===\nAfter a guard and a prisoner tested positive for coronavirus at [[Rikers Island]] prison, New York City Mayor Bill de Blasio said that city officials will identify individuals for release, including persons arrested for minor crimes and those most vulnerable to infection due to chronic health problems. In addition to the cases at Rikers, other prisons in the state, including [[Sing Sing]], have recorded positive tests among prisoners, and one member of the correction's department has died from the virus.<ref name=bbc>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51947802 \"US jails begin releasing prisoners to stem Covid-19 infections,\"] BBC News, March 19, 2020</ref>\n\nAs of March 25, 75 New York City inmates have tested positive for Covid-19 and 37 city corrections staff members, up from 50 inmates and 30 staffers the previous day. City jails are notoriously crowded, with beds often touching and in at least one instance, 29 people share a single toilet.<ref name=NY></ref>\n\n===Pennsylvania===\nDue to ongoing public health concerns related to the coronavirus, on March 13, [[Eastern State Penitentiary]] (a historic site which stopped operating as a prison in 1971) was closed to the public.<ref>[https://www.easternstate.org/ Eastern State Penitentiary,\"] accessed March 21, 2020</ref>\n\n===South Dakota===\nNine prisoners escaped from a minimal-security women's prison on March 23, the same day a fellow-inmate tested positive for Covid-19. Three were captured on the [[Crow Creek Indian Reservation]] and one was captured in [[Rapid City, South Dakota|Rapid City]]. It was not immediately clear if the diagnosis prompted the prisoners to run.<ref name=SD>[https://abcnews.go.com/US/inmates-bolt-south-dakota-prison-day-prisoner-tested/story?id=69789196 9 inmates bolt from South Dakota prison on same day a prisoner tested positive for coronavirus] By Bill Hutchinson, ABC News, 25 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n===Washington state===\nFourteen inmates escaped from the county jail in [[Yakima County, Washington|Yakima County]] on March 23. They used a table to break down an exit door and then climbed a fence. The U.S. Marshals Service offered rewards of up to $1,000 for information leading to the arrests of the escaped inmates.<ref name=SD></ref>\n\n===Wisconsin===\nThe first COVID-19 positive case in the Wisconsin state prison system, an employee at [[Waupun Correctional Institution]], was reported on March 18 by warden Brian Foster. Inmate advocacy groups called on the Department of Corrections and Governor [[Tony Evers]] to change prison policies to protect prisoners and guards during the epidemic.<ref>Emily Hamer, [https://madison.com/wsj/news/local/wisconsin-prison-employee-tests-positive-for-covid--inmate-advocates/article_724c81a5-61e8-5bb2-b5ac-24ba210a9a76.html \"Wisconsin prison employee tests positive for COVID-19; inmate advocates call for protections amid pandemic,\"] State Journal, March 20, 2020</ref>\n\n==Venezuela==\n''[[Reuters]]'' reported that Venezuela's notoriously overcrowded and unsanitary prisons could spread the coronavirus \"like a fast-moving fire.\" Venezuelan prisons frequently lack bathrooms, people sleep on floors, and many inmates spend their days without shirts or shoes on, in part to combat the infernal heat of windowless facilities.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ellsworth|first=Brian|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-prisons/overcrowded-and-unsanitary-venezuelas-prisons-brace-for-coronavirus-idUSKBN215323|title=Overcrowded and unsanitary, Venezuela's prisons brace for coronavirus|date=18 March 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live|last2=Sequera|first2=Vivian}}</ref> \n\nThis has caused [[United States Secretary of State|US Secretary of State]] [[Mike Pompeo]] to demand the Maduro government release six [[Citgo]] executives, held in prison since 2017, on humanitarian grounds.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=SecPompeo|number=1240617609441280002|date=19 March 2020|title=It is past time for the Maduro regime to release the #Citgo6 who are currently languishing in the notorious Helicoide prison in #Venezuela. 2+ years in prison with no evidence brought against them; 18 hearings cancelled. Unacceptable.|author=Secretary Pompeo}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" /> Pompeo said that all six men have weakened [[immune system]]s and \"face a grave health risk if they become infected\" with the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200319-us-demands-venezuela-free-citgo-executives-as-virus-hits|title=US demands Venezuela free Citgo executives as virus hits|date=19 March 2020|work=[[France 24]]|access-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live|agency=[[Agence France-Presse]]}}</ref> The Venezuelan Medical Federation asked for the release of the political prisoners in the country, specifically [[Roberto Marrero]], [[Juan Requesens]] and other lawmakers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lapatilla.com/2020/03/14/presidente-de-la-fmv-exhorta-a-que-se-liberen-a-presos-politicos-por-coronavirus/|title=Presidente de la FMV exhorta a que se liberen a presos pol\u00edticos por coronavirus|first=|date=14 March 2020|website=[[La Patilla]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, 84 out of 518 inmates escaped from a prison in San Carlos, [[Zulia]], after restrictions against the pandemic were announced, including jail visits. Mayor Bladimir Labrador declared that ten prisoners were killed during the prison break and that two policemen were detained for complicity. According to Carlos Nieto Palma from the NGO Ventana a la Libertad, the suspension of visits directly affects the prisoner's nutrition, given that there was no state-sponsored program to feed them.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.es/internacional/2020/03/19/5e72c06f21efa09a6a8b462a.html|title=Las restricciones por el coronavirus provocan una fuga de presos que deja 10 muertos en Venezuela|date=19 March 2020|website=[[El Mundo (Venezuela)|El Mundo]]|publisher=AFP|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The NGO Provea denounced \"grave human rights violations\" after a military spokesperson announced the \"neutralization\" of 35 escapees.  State authorities later declared that the there were eight deaths.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://talcualdigital.com/provea-denuncia-asesinato-de-35-presos-fugados-de-reten-en-zulia/|title=Provea denuncia asesinato de 35 presos fugados de ret\u00e9n en Zulia|last=|first=|date=18 March 2020|website=[[Tal Cual]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Prisons]]\n[[Category:Prison healthcare]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Expand months", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impact_of_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic_on_prisons"}
{"title_page": "Bethesda Game Studios Austin", "text_new": "{{Redirect|BattleCry (video game)|other games|Battle Cry (disambiguation)#Games}}\n{{Use American English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Bethesda Game Studios Austin LLC\n| former_names = BattleCry Studios LLC (2012\u20132018)\n| logo =\n| type = [[Subsidiary]]\n| industry = [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|2012|10|03}}\n| founder = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| hq_location_city = [[Austin, Texas]]\n| hq_location_country = US\n| key_people =  Doug Mellencamp ([[studio director]])\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = {{Unbulleted list|[[ZeniMax Media]] {{small|(2012\u20132018)}}|[[Bethesda Game Studios]] {{small|(2018\u2013present)}}}}\n| website = {{URL|battlecrystudios.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Bethesda Game Studios Austin LLC''' (formerly '''BattleCry Studios LLC''') is an American [[video game developer]] based in [[Austin, Texas]].\n\n== History ==\nBattleCry Studios was founded on October 3, 2012, as [[subsidiary]] of [[ZeniMax Media]], headed by Rich Vogel as its [[President (corporate title)|president]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2012/10/03/battlecry-studios-is-new-austin-based-studio-from-bethesda-softw/ |title=Battlecry Studios is new Austin-based developer from Bethesda Softworks |last=Sliwinski |first=Alexander |date=October 3, 2012 |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[AOL Tech]] |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref> Initially, BattleCry Studios was seeking employees with experience in [[microtransaction]]s and [[free-to-play]] games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2012/10/04/bethesdas-new-battlecry-studios-looking-for-f2p-experts/ |title=Bethesda's new Battlecry Studios looking for F2P experts |last=Reahard |first=Jef |date=October 4, 2012 |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[AOL Tech]] |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn May 28, 2014, BattleCry Studios announced their first game, ''BattleCry''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/gaming/2014/05/28/bethesda-battlecry/9665925/ |title=Bethesda unveils free-to-play game 'Battlecry' |last=Molina |first=Brett |date=May 28, 2014 |website=[[USA Today]] |publisher=[[Gannett Satellite Information Network]] |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref> On September 10, 2015, it was reported that BattleCry Studios had laid off a \"substantial portion\" of their staff.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://theamericangenius.com/business-news/battlecry-studios-lays-off-unknown-number-of-staff-in-austin/ |title=BattleCry Studios lays off unknown number of staff in Austin |last=Rosales |first=Lani |date=September 10, 2015 |website=[[The American Genius]] |publisher=[[AGBeat]] |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref> On October 7, 2015, the development on ''BattleCry'' was halted for the studio to work on different projects.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pcgamer.com/bethesda-has-concerns-about-battlecry-and-is-evaluating-it/ |title=Bethesda has 'concerns' about Battlecry and is 'evaluating' it |last=Prescott |first=Shaun |date=October 8, 2015 |website=[[PC Gamer]] |publisher=[[Future US]] |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref> One of the studio's first projects following the hold of ''BattleCry'' was the modification and restructuring of Bethesda's [[Creation Engine]] (in conjunction with sister company [[id Software]], utilizing [[netcode]] from ''[[Quake (series)|Quake]]'') to support multiplayer functionality in anticipation of then upcoming ''[[Fallout 76]]''.<ref name=\"noclip\">{{cite web |author1=Noclip |title=The Making of Fallout 76 - Noclip Documentary |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gi8PTAJ2Hjs |website=YouTube |accessdate=June 17, 2018 |date=June 12, 2018|author1-link=Noclip }}</ref> In September 2017, Vogel announced that he had left BattleCry Studios in favor of [[Certain Affinity]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-09-22-rich-vogel-joins-certain-affinity |title=Rich Vogel joins Certain Affinity |last=Sinclair |first=Brendan |date=September 22, 2017 |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]] |publisher=[[Gamer Network]] |accessdate=September 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, the studio was rebranded as Bethesda Game Studios Austin, making it the third studio under the [[Bethesda Game Studios]] banner within Bethesda Softworks.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-03-09-battlecry-studios-becomes-third-bethesda-game-studios-office | title = BattleCry Studios becomes third Bethesda Game Studios office | first = Christopher | last = Dring | date = March 9, 2018 | accessdate = March 9, 2018 | work = [[GamesIndustry.biz]] }}</ref>\n\n== Games developed ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Platform(s)\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Doom (2016 video game)|Doom]]''\n| [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Xbox One]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Nintendo Switch]]\n| Replaced [[Certain Affinity]] on assisting [[id Software]] with development of post-release multiplayer content.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Holmes|first1=Mike|date=August 6, 2016|title=BattleCry devs now working with id on Doom multiplayer|url=http://www.gamereactor.eu/news/443533/BattleCry+devs+now+working+with+id+on+Doom+multiplayer/|website=[[Gamereactor UK]]|accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Fallout 76]]''\n| [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Xbox One]], [[PlayStation 4]]\n| Additional work in the game.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Schreier|first1=Jason|date=May 30, 2018|title=Bethesda Announces Fallout: 76|url=https://kotaku.com/bethesda-announces-fallout-76-1826417383|website=[[Kotaku]]|accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|battlecrystudios.com}}\n\n{{ZeniMax Media}}\n\n[[Category:Video game companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Video game development companies]]\n[[Category:ZeniMax Media]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Austin, Texas]]\n[[Category:Video game companies established in 2012]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in Texas]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Texas]]\n\n\n{{US-videogame-company-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|BattleCry (video game)|other games|Battle Cry (disambiguation)#Games}}\n{{Use American English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Bethesda Game Studios Austin LLC\n| former_names = BattleCry Studios LLC (2012\u20132018)\n| logo =\n| type = [[Subsidiary]]\n| industry = [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|2012|10|03}}\n| founder = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| hq_location_city = [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], [[Texas]]\n| hq_location_country = U.S.\n| key_people =  Doug Mellencamp ([[studio director]])\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = {{Unbulleted list|[[ZeniMax Media]] {{small|(2012\u20132018)}}|[[Bethesda Game Studios]] {{small|(2018\u2013present)}}}}\n| website = {{URL|battlecrystudios.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Bethesda Game Studios Austin LLC''' (formerly '''BattleCry Studios LLC''') is an American [[video game developer]] based in [[Austin, Texas]].\n\n== History ==\nBattleCry Studios was founded on October 3, 2012, as [[subsidiary]] of [[ZeniMax Media]], headed by Rich Vogel as its [[President (corporate title)|president]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2012/10/03/battlecry-studios-is-new-austin-based-studio-from-bethesda-softw/ |title=Battlecry Studios is new Austin-based developer from Bethesda Softworks |last=Sliwinski |first=Alexander |date=October 3, 2012 |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[AOL Tech]] |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref> Initially, BattleCry Studios was seeking employees with experience in [[microtransaction]]s and [[free-to-play]] games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2012/10/04/bethesdas-new-battlecry-studios-looking-for-f2p-experts/ |title=Bethesda's new Battlecry Studios looking for F2P experts |last=Reahard |first=Jef |date=October 4, 2012 |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[AOL Tech]] |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn May 28, 2014, BattleCry Studios announced their first game, ''BattleCry''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/gaming/2014/05/28/bethesda-battlecry/9665925/ |title=Bethesda unveils free-to-play game 'Battlecry' |last=Molina |first=Brett |date=May 28, 2014 |website=[[USA Today]] |publisher=[[Gannett Satellite Information Network]] |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref> On September 10, 2015, it was reported that BattleCry Studios had laid off a \"substantial portion\" of their staff.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://theamericangenius.com/business-news/battlecry-studios-lays-off-unknown-number-of-staff-in-austin/ |title=BattleCry Studios lays off unknown number of staff in Austin |last=Rosales |first=Lani |date=September 10, 2015 |website=[[The American Genius]] |publisher=[[AGBeat]] |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref> On October 7, 2015, the development on ''BattleCry'' was halted for the studio to work on different projects.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pcgamer.com/bethesda-has-concerns-about-battlecry-and-is-evaluating-it/ |title=Bethesda has 'concerns' about Battlecry and is 'evaluating' it |last=Prescott |first=Shaun |date=October 8, 2015 |website=[[PC Gamer]] |publisher=[[Future US]] |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref> One of the studio's first projects following the hold of ''BattleCry'' was the modification and restructuring of Bethesda's [[Creation Engine]] (in conjunction with sister company [[id Software]], utilizing [[netcode]] from ''[[Quake (series)|Quake]]'') to support multiplayer functionality in anticipation of then upcoming ''[[Fallout 76]]''.<ref name=\"noclip\">{{cite web |author1=Noclip |title=The Making of Fallout 76 - Noclip Documentary |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gi8PTAJ2Hjs |website=YouTube |accessdate=June 17, 2018 |date=June 12, 2018|author1-link=Noclip }}</ref> In September 2017, Vogel announced that he had left BattleCry Studios in favor of [[Certain Affinity]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-09-22-rich-vogel-joins-certain-affinity |title=Rich Vogel joins Certain Affinity |last=Sinclair |first=Brendan |date=September 22, 2017 |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]] |publisher=[[Gamer Network]] |accessdate=September 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, the studio was rebranded as Bethesda Game Studios Austin, making it the third studio under the [[Bethesda Game Studios]] banner within Bethesda Softworks.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-03-09-battlecry-studios-becomes-third-bethesda-game-studios-office | title = BattleCry Studios becomes third Bethesda Game Studios office | first = Christopher | last = Dring | date = March 9, 2018 | accessdate = March 9, 2018 | work = [[GamesIndustry.biz]] }}</ref>\n\n== Games developed ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Platform(s)\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Doom (2016 video game)|Doom]]''\n| [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Xbox One]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Nintendo Switch]]\n| Replaced [[Certain Affinity]] on assisting [[id Software]] with development of post-release multiplayer content.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Holmes|first1=Mike|date=August 6, 2016|title=BattleCry devs now working with id on Doom multiplayer|url=http://www.gamereactor.eu/news/443533/BattleCry+devs+now+working+with+id+on+Doom+multiplayer/|website=[[Gamereactor UK]]|accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Fallout 76]]''\n| [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Xbox One]], [[PlayStation 4]]\n| Additional work in the game.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Schreier|first1=Jason|date=May 30, 2018|title=Bethesda Announces Fallout: 76|url=https://kotaku.com/bethesda-announces-fallout-76-1826417383|website=[[Kotaku]]|accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|battlecrystudios.com}}\n\n{{ZeniMax Media}}\n\n[[Category:Video game companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Video game development companies]]\n[[Category:ZeniMax Media]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Austin, Texas]]\n[[Category:Video game companies established in 2012]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in Texas]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Texas]]\n\n\n{{US-videogame-company-stub}}\n", "name_user": "IceWelder", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bethesda_Game_Studios_Austin"}
{"title_page": "Ex on the Beach (British series 11)", "text_new": "{{Short description|Eleventh series of Ex on the Beach}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox television season\n| bgcolour             = #2CB46C\n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| country              = [[United Kingdom]]\n| network              = [[MTV (UK and Ireland)|MTV]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2020|01|21|df=y}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|present|df=y}}\n| num_episodes         =\n| prev_series          = [[Ex on the Beach (British series 9)|Series 9]]\n| next_series          = \n| season_number        = 11\n| image_alt            = \n| starring             = \n| released             = \n| episode_list         = \n}}\n\nThe '''eleventh series''' of ''[[Ex on the Beach]]'' began airing on 21 January 2020 with a 90-minute special.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/reality-tv/a30162203/celebrity-ex-on-the-beach-line-up-mtv-2020-joey-essex-calum-best/|title=Celebrity Ex on the Beach confirms Joey Essex and Love Island's Georgia Harrison on official line-up|first=Chris|last=Edwards|date=9 December 2019|work=[[Digital Spy]]}}</ref> This series is billed as ''\"Celebrity Ex on the Beach\"'' as for the first time, it features a set of famous cast members. The series was filmed in [[Marbella]].\n\nThe series follows the cancellation of the tenth series, which was set to air in early 2019, which was cancelled due to the death of cast member [[Mike Thalassitis]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ohmymag.co.uk/love-island/the-next-series-of-ex-on-the-beach-has-been-cancelled-following-mike-thalassitis-death_art3561.html|title=The Next Series Of Ex On The Beach Has Been Cancelled Following Mike Thalassitis' Death|date=20 March 2019|work=Oh My|language=en|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/reality-tv/a26880794/ex-on-the-beach-series-10-mike-thalassitis-pulled-from-air/|title=Ex on the Beach's new series pulled by MTV after Mike Thalassitis death|last=Houghton|first=Rianne|date=20 March 2019|work=[[Digital Spy]]|language=en|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref> None of the other cast members for the tenth series were announced.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/07/17/mtvs-ex-beach-set-return-year-season-10-pulled-wake-love-island-star-mike-thalassitis-death-10379143/|title=Ex On The Beach 'set to return this year' after Mike Thalassitis death|last=Deen|first=Sarah|access-date=8 August 2019|work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\nThe list of celebrity cast members was released on 9 December 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tellymix.co.uk/reality-tv/ex-on-the-beach/414121-ex-on-the-beach-2020-cast-season-11-start-date.html|title=Celebrity Ex On The Beach cast and start date confirmed for 2020|first=Josh|last=Darvill|date=22 December 2019|work=TellyMix}}</ref> They include four men; Olympic athlete [[Ashley McKenzie]], television personality [[Calum Best]], ''[[The Only Way Is Essex]]'' star [[Joey Essex]], and ''[[Love Island (2015 TV series, series 5)|Love Island]]'' star Michael Griffiths, and four women; ''Love Island'' star Georgia Harrison, ''[[The Valleys (TV series)|The Valleys]]'' star [[Lateysha Grace]], playboy model [[Lorena Medina]] and ''[[Mob Wives]]'' star Marissa Jade.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.realitytitbit.com/whats-on/meet-the-celebrity-ex-on-the-beach-2020-cast-ashley-mckenzie-to-michael-griffiths|title=Meet the Celebrity Ex on the Beach 2020 cast: Ashley McKenzie to Michael Griffiths!|date=10 December 2019}}</ref> It was also announced that the exes joining the series would be celebrities.\n\nEllie Brown, star of the [[Love Island (2015 TV series, series 4)|fourth series]] of ''Love Island'' was the first ex to arrive, hoping to rekindle a relationship with Essex, her ex-boyfriend.\n\n*'''Bold''' indicates original cast member; all other cast were brought into the series as an ex.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Episodes !! Name !! Age (at start of series) !! Notability !! Exes\n|-\n| 12\n| '''[[Ashley McKenzie]]'''\n| 30\n| Olympian\n| Danielle Kedward\n|-\n| 12\n| '''[[Calum Best]]'''\n| 38\n| TV personality\n| Ayesha Reid, Marissa Jade, Megan Rapley, Victoria Winterford\n|-\n| 12\n| '''Georgia Harrison'''\n| 24\n| ''[[Love Island (2015 TV series, series 3)|Love Island]]'' star\n| Miles Nazaire\n|-\n| 12\n| '''[[Joey Essex]]'''\n| 29\n| ''[[The Only Way Is Essex]]'' star\n| Ellie Brown\n|-\n| 12\n| '''[[Lateysha Grace]]'''\n| 26\n| ''[[The Valleys (TV series)|The Valleys]]'' star\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| 12\n| '''[[Lorena Medina]]'''\n| 27\n| Model\n| Itay Ohayon, Patrick Hale\n|-\n| 12\n| '''[[Marissa Jade]]'''\n| 34\n| ''[[Mob Wives]]'' star\n| Calum Best\n|-\n| 12\n| '''Michael Griffiths'''\n| 27\n| ''[[Love Island (2015 TV series, series 5)|Love Island]]'' star\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n! style=\"background:#000;\" colspan=\"6\"|\n|-\n| 12\n| Ellie Brown\n| 21\n| ''[[Love Island (2015 TV series, series 4)|Love Island]]'' star\n| Charlie Brake, Joey Essex\n|-\n| 11\n| [[David McIntosh (Gladiators)|David McIntosh]]\n| 34\n| Media personality\n| Metisha Schaefer, Tiffany Pollard\n|-\n|-\n| 8\n| Victoria Winterford\n| 26\n| ''[[Celebs Go Dating (series 3)|Celebs Go Dating]]'' star\n| Calum Best, Lotan Carter \n|-\n|-\n| 3\n| Itay Ohayon\n| 26\n| Model\n| Lorena Medina\n|-\n|-\n| 4\n| Danielle Kedward\n| 29\n| Glamour model\n| Ashley McKenzie\n|-\n|-\n| 4\n| Charlie Brake\n| 24\n| ''[[Love Island (2015 TV series, series 4)|Love Island]]'' star\n| Ellie Brown\n|-\n|-\n| 7\n| Sophie Kasaei\n| 30\n| ''[[Geordie Shore]]'' star\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| 5\n| [[Tiffany Pollard]]\n| 38\n| TV personality\n| David McIntosh\n|-\n| 3\n| Lotan Carter\n| 30\n| ''[[Big Brother (British series 18)|Big Brother]]'' star\n| Victoria Winterford\n|-\n| 4\n| Patrick Hale\n| 20\n| Model and Singer\n| Lorena Medina\n|-\n| 1\n| Ayesha Reid\n| 26